'''John Francis Souttar''' (born 25 September 1996) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]. He previously played for [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] and [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] before joining Rangers in 2022.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Rangers Sign John Souttar on Pre-Contract Agreement|url=https://www.rangers.co.uk/article/rangers-sign-john-souttar-on-pre-contract-agreement/2zAMNHHbj4shK7t0EFceze|access-date=2022-01-14|publisher=Rangers F.C.|language=en-gb|website=www.rangers.co.uk}}</ref>

Known as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]], Souttar was converted to play as a [[midfielder]] towards the end of his stay at Dundee United, however he reverted to once again playing as a centre-back for Hearts.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Winners and Losers: Kieran Tierney {{!}} John Souttar {{!}} Hearts fans |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/competitions/premiership/winners-and-losers-kieran-tierney-john-souttar-hearts-fans-1-4053887 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20180831072031/https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/competitions/premiership/winners-and-losers-kieran-tierney-john-souttar-hearts-fans-1-4053887 |archive-date=2018-08-31 |access-date=2026-05-20 |language=en}}</ref> He is the youngest player to have appeared for Dundee United's first team, having made his debut for the club in January 2013 at the age of 16. After previously representing the country at [[Scotland national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[Scotland national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels, he made his full international debut in September 2018.

==Early life==
Souttar was born on 25 September 1996 in [[Aberdeen]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/teams/players/250056853--john-souttar/ | title=John Souttar | publisher=[[UEFA]] | access-date=2 January 2013}}</ref> to parents Jack and Heather. His father had previously been a professional footballer, with [[Brechin City F.C.|Brechin City]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=John Souttar: From Howe o' the Mearns to Heart of Midlothian |url=https://www.mearnsleader.co.uk/sport/football/john-souttar-howe-o-mearns-heart-midlothian-2108356 |access-date=2026-05-20 |website=The Scotsman |language=en}}</ref> His mother was born in Australia.<ref name=AUS/> Growing up in the village of [[Luthermuir]], Aberdeenshire, Souttar attended Luthermuir Primary and then [[Mearns Academy]] in nearby [[Laurencekirk]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mearnsleader.co.uk/sport/john-capped-for-scotland-u17s-1-2513224|title=John capped for Scotland U17s |publisher=Mearns Leader|work=mearnsleader.co.uk|date=8 September 2012|access-date=2 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mearns youngsters extend contracts for Dundee United|url=http://www.mearnsleader.co.uk/sport/local-sport/mearns-youngsters-extend-contracts-for-dundee-united-1-2781269|access-date=9 September 2015|work=Mearns Leader|date=8 February 2013|location=Stonehaven}}</ref>

In 2002, Souttar began to play for Brechin City Boys Club (later Brechin City Youths), where he was coached by his father in a successful team also containing [[Ryan Gauld]] and [[Euan Spark]]. The trio also developed their skills at coaching schools run in Dundee by [[Ian Cathro]], before joining [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]'s youth system in 2006 at the age of nine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brechincityyouths.co.uk/club/History|title=Former Players with Senior Clubs|publisher=Brechin Boys Club|work=brechincityyouths.co.uk|date=1 October 2011|access-date=2 January 2013|archive-date=3 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170103000005/http://www.brechincityyouths.co.uk/club/History|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Souttar has a younger brother,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Liam|title=Dundee United youth coach: John Souttar's had a tough summer but I know his time will come|url=http://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/2014/08/22/dundee-united-youth-coach-john-souttars-had-a-tough-summer-but-i-know-his-time-will-come/|access-date=16 September 2015|work=Eventing Telegraph|date=22 August 2014|location=Dundee}}</ref> [[Harry Souttar|Harry]], who plays for [[Leicester City]] and is an [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australian]] international.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Stoke City sign teenage defender Harry Souttar from Dundee United |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11701/10598328/stoke-city-sign-teenage-defender-harry-souttar-from-dundee-united |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20241210160633/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11701/10598328/stoke-city-sign-teenage-defender-harry-souttar-from-dundee-united |archive-date=2024-12-10 |access-date=2026-05-20 |work=Sky Sports |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.socceroos.com.au/news/conversation-which-sparked-souttars-australia-call |title=The conversation that sparked Souttar's Australia call-up |first=Jacob |last=Windon |date=1 June 2019 |accessdate=28 September 2021 |website=socceroos.com.au |publisher=Football Australia}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=sport |first=Guardian |date=2023-01-31 |title=Australia’s Harry Souttar makes Premier League move to Leicester City |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/feb/01/australias-harry-souttar-makes-premier-league-move-to-leicester-city |access-date=2026-05-20 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Dundee United===

After progressing through the various youth team levels at Dundee United, Souttar signed a professional contract in July 2012 and became a member of the club's under-20 development squad.<ref name=DUFC>{{cite web|title=First Team&nbsp;— John Souttar|url=http://dufc.co/the-teams/first-team/6087/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140911154408/http://dufc.co/the-teams/first-team/6087/|url-status=usurped|archive-date=11 September 2014|publisher=Dundee United F.C.|access-date=9 September 2015}}</ref> After just four months in the development team, injuries and suspensions led to Souttar making his first team debut on 2 January 2013, playing in [[central defender|central defence]] from the start in a 2–2 draw with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] at [[Pittodrie Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Aberdeen v Dundee Utd - 2nd Jan 2013 {{!}} Report {{!}} Scots Prem {{!}} Sky Sports Football |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/262067/report |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20140101103805/http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/262067/report |archive-date=2014-01-01 |access-date=2026-05-20 |website=www1.skysports.com |language=en}}</ref> Aged 16 years and 99 days, he became the youngest ever player to play for Dundee United.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20843051 | title=Aberdeen 2–2 Dundee United |publisher=BBC Sport | date=2 January 2013 | access-date=2 January 2013}}</ref> 

On 24 January 2013, Souttar signed a contract extension keeping him at the club until January 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21190697 | title=Ryan Gauld and John Souttar extend contracts |publisher=BBC Sport | date=24 January 2013 | access-date=24 January 2013}}</ref> Still aged 16, Souttar returned to the first team in April 2013 following an injury to [[Brian McLean]] and started regularly for the remainder of the season, playing against [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in a 4–3 [[Scottish Cup]] semi-final defeat on 14 April 2013 at [[Hampden Park]].<ref name="DUFC" />

Souttar's form began to attract the attention of other clubs, with English [[Premier League]] team [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] having a bid of £600,000 accepted by Dundee United in October 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dundee United defender John Souttar knocks back move to Sunderland after Terrors agree £600k bid|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-transfer-news/dundee-united-defender-john-souttar-2659566|access-date=10 September 2015|work=Daily Record|date=31 October 2013|location=Glasgow}}</ref> After speaking to Sunderland officials, Souttar decided to turn down the transfer. On 4 November 2013, Souttar signed another extension to his contract, keeping him at Dundee United until May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dundee Utd: Ryan Gauld and John Souttar extend their contracts|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24812193|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 November 2013|access-date=7 November 2013}}</ref> Souttar continued to play regularly in central defence throughout the 2013–14 season and scored his first goal for the club in a [[Scottish Premiership]] match against Aberdeen on 1 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dundee Utd 1–2 Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25513221|publisher=BBC Sport|date=1 January 2014|access-date=2 January 2014}}</ref>

Souttar missed the first three months of the 2014–15 season due to an ankle injury sustained in pre-season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Swan|first1=Craig|title=Dundee United's John Souttar: How could I moan about my op when mate Jordan was battling cancer?|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/dundee-uniteds-john-souttar-how-4726012|access-date=14 September 2015|work=Daily Record|date=1 December 2014}}</ref> After his return to the first team, Dundee United successfully experimented with Souttar in a defensive midfield role in matches against Celtic and Aberdeen during April 2015, a position in which he has subsequently featured regularly.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roache|first1=Ian|title=Dundee United's John Souttar right at home in midfield|url=http://www.thecourier.co.uk/sport/football/dundee-united/dundee-united-s-john-souttar-right-at-home-in-midfield-1.869857|access-date=14 September 2015|work=The Courier|date=29 April 2015|location=Dundee}}</ref> In October 2015, new United head coach [[Mixu Paatelainen]] played Souttar at [[right back]] in his first two matches in charge.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nicolson|first1=Eric|title=Dundee United's John Souttar can be a 'top, top' right-back, says Mixu|url=http://www.thecourier.co.uk/sport/football/st-johnstone/dundee-united-s-john-souttar-can-be-a-top-top-right-back-says-mixu-1.907369|access-date=29 October 2015|work=The Courier|date=29 October 2015|location=Dundee|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151102023724/http://www.thecourier.co.uk/sport/football/st-johnstone/dundee-united-s-john-souttar-can-be-a-top-top-right-back-says-mixu-1.907369|archive-date=2 November 2015}}</ref> In all he made seventy three appearances in all competitions, scoring twice.<ref name = "Soc"/>

===Heart of Midlothian===
On 1 February 2016, Souttar signed for fellow Scottish Premiership club [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]], agreeing a three-and-a-half-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Souttar Signs|url=http://www.heartsfc.co.uk/news/4935|publisher=Heart of Midlothian F.C.|date=1 February 2016|access-date=1 February 2016}}</ref> Speaking about his move Souttar said that he was "looking forward to getting stuck in and getting my career back on track".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35466803 | title=Hearts complete deal for Dundee United defender | publisher=BBC Sport | date=2 February 2016 | access-date=2 February 2016}}</ref>

Souttar played regularly for Hearts during the 2016–17 season until he suffered a ruptured [[achilles tendon]] during a match against [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in January 2017 which ended his season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38814559 |title=John Souttar: Hearts defender ruled out for rest of season |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 February 2017 |access-date=3 February 2017}}</ref> He made a full recovery (though then missed three months in late 2018 with a hip injury which was aggravated on international duty),<ref name="McLeish">{{cite news|url=https://www.thenational.scot/sport/17007048.alex-mcleish-hearts-scotland-centre-half-john-souttar-will-stronger-fitter-makes-comeback/|title=Alex McLeish: Hearts and Scotland centre half John Souttar will be stronger and fitter when he makes his comeback|last=Lindsay|first=Matthew|date=25 October 2018|work=The National|access-date=2026-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pilcher |first=Ross |date=26 October 2018 |title=Hearts defender shares post-operation update |url=https://www.edinburghlive.co.uk/news/hearts-john-souttar-gives-injury-15331874 |website=Edinburgh Live |language=en|access-date=2026-05-20}}</ref> and took part in the run to the [[2019 Scottish Cup Final]] which Hearts lost to the same opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=539373|title=Celtic clinch 'Triple Treble' with Scottish Cup win|date=25 May 2019|publisher=ESPN|access-date=9 August 2020}}</ref>

After missing much of the [[2019–20 Heart of Midlothian F.C. season|2019–20 season]] with an ankle injury requiring an operation, Souttar returned to the team only to tear the achilles in his other leg during a Scottish Cup tie with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in February 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51693447 |title=Scotland: Scott McKenna and John Souttar injuries blow to play-off hopes |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 February 2020 |access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> Initially fearing his career was over, the recovery took six months.<ref name=hell>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/john-souttar-opens-up-hearts-22490589 |title=John Souttar opens up on Hearts injury hell as he admits he feared career was over |last=McDermott |first=Scott |date=9 August 2020 |work=Sunday Mail |access-date=9 August 2020 }}</ref> Due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in Scotland]], the 2019–20 Scottish league season was curtailed and Hearts were consequently relegated.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53526063 |title=Hearts & Partick Thistle relegations confirmed by arbitration panel |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 July 2020 |access-date=9 August 2020}}</ref> Soon after returning to training, Souttar snapped the same achilles tendon that had been injured earlier in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53875788 |title=John Souttar: Hearts defender suffers 'relapse' of achilles injury |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 August 2020 |access-date=24 August 2020}}</ref>

=== Rangers ===

On 14 January 2022, [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] announced Souttar had signed a pre-contract agreement to bring him to the club at the end of the [[2021–22 Scottish Premiership|2021–22 season]] once his contract with Hearts runs out.<ref name=":0" /> The move was completed on 1 June 2022.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/john-souttar-im-physically-and-mentally-ready-to-join-rangers |title=John Souttar: I'm physically and mentally ready to join Rangers |first=Lewis |last=McKenzie |website=STV Sport |date=1 June 2022 |accessdate=1 June 2022}}</ref> He made his debut for the club against [[Scottish Premiership]] side [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]], starting the match, in a 2–1 win on 30 July.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2022-07-30 |title=Livingston 1-2 Rangers: Visitors open with win after two goals in two minutes |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62275140 |access-date=2026-05-20 |work=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>  

Souttar suffered injury problems during the 2022–23 season and did not play for Rangers again until early March.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/john-souttar-rangers-respect-felt-29380569 |title=John Souttar and the Rangers respect felt through the dressing room as team-mates have his back |newspaper=Daily Record |first=Andrew |last=Newport |date=6 March 2023 |accessdate=14 May 2023}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 13 May 2023, in a 3–0 [[Old Firm]] derby win against [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Fassihi |first=Mazzetti |date=2026-05-19 |title=nowgoal |url=https://nowgoal.tel |access-date=2026-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/cx9nrldyq4eo |title=Souttar 'feeling good' and ready to become 'mainstay' |website=BBC Sport |date=14 May 2023 |accessdate=14 May 2023}}</ref>

==International career==
Souttar has represented Scotland at [[Scotland national under-17 football team|under-17]] level,<ref name="Scot">{{cite web | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=1848&playerID=114832&squadID=13 | title=John Souttar Under–17 | publisher=[[Scottish Football Association]]  | access-date=2 January 2013}}</ref> making his debut on 28 August 2012, in a 0–0 draw against [[Belgium national under-17 football team|Belgium]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=1921&matchID=120262 | title=Scotland v Belgium | publisher=[[Scottish Football Association]] | date=28 August 2012 | access-date=2 January 2013}}</ref> In May 2013, Souttar made his debut<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=2492&playerID=114832&squadID=9 | title=U19 Squad Matches | publisher=[[Scottish Football Association]] | access-date=1 February 2016}}</ref> for the [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland under-19]] team, against [[England national under-19 football team|England]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=1921&matchID=128381 | title=England compound Scotland Under-19s' Euro misery | publisher=[[Scottish Football Association]] | date=29 May 2013 | access-date=1 February 2016}}</ref>

[[Alex McLeish]] called Souttar into the senior [[Scotland national football team|Scotland squad]] for the first time in May 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44111727 |title=Scotland pick Johnny Russell plus seven uncapped players including Lewis Stevenson & Lewis Morgan |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 May 2018 |access-date=14 May 2018}}</ref> but he was forced to withdraw due to hip and hamstring injuries.<ref>{{cite news |first=Barry |last=Anderson |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts/surgery-fear-for-john-souttar-as-hearts-defender-forced-out-of-scotland-squad-1-4742570 |title=Surgery fear for John Souttar as Hearts defender forced out of Scotland squad |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=21 May 2018 |access-date=21 May 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, Souttar's manager at [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]], [[Craig Levein]], suggested that Souttar may be called up for [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] if not selected for Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://au.eurosport.com/football/scotland-risk-losing-john-souttar-to-australia-craig-levein_sto6897970/story.shtml|title=Scotland risk losing John Souttar to Australia – Craig Levein|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|date=23 August 2018|access-date=16 October 2018}}</ref> Souttar later admitted he had not considered playing for Australia or been contacted by [[Football Federation Australia]], and that he was unaware Levein was going to make the suggestion.<ref name=AUS>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/hearts-star-john-souttar-admits-13199266|title=Hearts star John Souttar admits Craig Levein mischief over 'Australian granny' comment|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] |date=5 September 2018|access-date=16 October 2018|last=Jackson |first=Keith}}</ref>

Souttar was again selected for Scotland in September 2018, and he made his full international debut in a 4–0 defeat against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] on 7 September.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/ruthless-belgium-display-a-learning-curve-for-hearts-john-souttar-1-4796976 |title='Ruthless' Belgium display a learning curve for Hearts' John Souttar |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=7 September 2018 |access-date=11 September 2018 |first=Barry |last=Anderson}}</ref> A month later, in his third appearance, he was sent off for two bookings in a 2–1 loss away to [[Israel national football team|Israel]], later stating that he had been suffering with a hip injury (which caused him to miss three months of club football) but chose not to ask to be substituted as his defensive colleague [[Charlie Mulgrew]] had already come off injured.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-01-08 |title=Hearts' John Souttar: My desire to play through pain for Scotland led to red card |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts-john-souttar-my-desire-to-play-through-pain-for-scotland-led-to-red-card-179911 |access-date=2026-05-20 |website=Edinburgh News |language=en}}</ref>

In November 2021, Souttar was called up by [[Steve Clarke]] to the Scotland squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] qualifiers against [[Moldova national football team|Moldova]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]. On 15 November he scored his first international goal, a header from a corner, against Denmark in a 2–0 home win.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Scotland beat Danes to secure seeding|publisher=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59202146|access-date=2021-11-15}}</ref>

Souttar was named in the provisional squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]], but was omitted from the final list.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cjmm73ny1ddo |title=Scotland to cut Craig Gordon & John Souttar from Euros squad |website=BBC Sport |date=7 June 2024 |accessdate=8 June 2024}}</ref> Called up for [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League]] fixtures against [[Poland national football team|Poland]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] and [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], he was named player of the match against Portugal as Scotland earned a point from a 0–0 draw at Hampden, and was joined on the field by childhood companion Ryan Gauld, the first time they had played together since their Dundee United spell in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sport |first=P. A. |date=2024-10-16 |title='It’s amazing': Souttar loving Scotland reunion with childhood friend Gauld |url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/its-amazing-john-souttar-loving-scotland-reunion-with-childhood-friend-ryan-gauld |access-date=2026-05-20 |website=STV News |language=en-GB}}</ref>

